(138, 'Aims & Scope', 10, 28, 'aims-scope', 'journal-of-syndromes', '<div class="eb-box"><p>The Journal of Syndromes is an international, Online Open Access, peer reviewed journal encompassing a wide spectrum of syndromes which are caused due to physical, mental, genetical, metabolic, environmental and other factors that commonly anguish and effects living organisms.</p></div><p>Topics covered in this Journal include, but are not limited to:</p><ul><li>Genetical Syndromes</li><li>Environmental Syndromes</li><li>Cardiovascular Syndromes</li><li>Neoplastic Syndromes</li><li>Congenital Syndromes</li><li>Infectious Syndromes</li><li>Anonymous Syndromes</li><li>Case Reports</li><li>Rett Syndrome</li><li>Inflammatory Bowel Diseases</li><li>Brugada Syndrome</li><li>Cowden Syndrome</li><li>Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome</li></ul>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1),
(139, 'Editorial Board', 10, 28, 'editorial-board', 'journal-of-syndromes', '<div class="eb-box"><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/pic11.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-14460"/><p></p><p><strong>Dr. Francis I. Achike</strong> is a Professor of Pharmacology and Clinical Skills at the Central Michigan University College of Medicine, USA. His research interest spans medical education and cardiovascular pharmacology with bias for diabetes and the metabolic syndrome.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/BSG-photo1.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-14506"/><p></p><p><strong>Dr. Barry Scott George</strong> is an Associate Professor of Clinical Medicine, Cardiology at The Ohio State University, USA. His research interests focuses on interventional cardiology, endovascular therapies, structural heart disease and development of novel endovascular devices to address complex repair of aortic aneurysms with fenestrated endovascular grafts has also been part of his contribution.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Prado_Vania.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3433"/><p></p><p><strong>Dr. Vania Prado</strong> is an Associate Professor at the Departments of Anatomy and Cell Biology, and Physiology and Pharmacology, Western University, Canada. She is also a Scientist of the Robarts Research Institute.  She uses genetically modified mice that model cholinergic dysfunction to understand the physiological roles of acetylcholine in the brain and in the peripheral nervous system.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/7.jpg" alt="" title="7" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3544"/><p></p><p><strong>Dr. Gang Dong</strong> is an Associate Professor, Department of Medical Biochemistry at the Medical University of Vienna, Austria. His research focuses on structural characterization of centriole &amp;  cilium biogenesis including intraflagellar transport, flagellar pocket formation, vesicle targeting to the cilium &amp; centriole/basal body duplication.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/photo-21.jpg" alt="" title="7" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17485"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Xu Zeng</strong> is an Associate Professor in the Department of Pathology and Laboratory Medicine at Temple University Hospital, USA. His research interests focuses on surgical pathologist with subspecialty expertise in the area of medical kidney disease and kidney/pancreas transplantation.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/photo-bw-Signorelli-1.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17490"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Francesco Signorelli</strong> is an Associate Professor of Neurosurgery at the University Hospital of Catanzaro, Italy. His current major interests are vascular neurosurgery and brain tumors in eloquent areas. Surgical and endovascular treatment of brain vascular malformations is a significant portion of his practice.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Lizhong-Wang.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3140"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Lizhong Wang </strong> is an  Assistant Professor at the Department of Genetics &amp; Associate Scientist Comprehensive Cancer Center School of Medicine, University of Alabama, USA. His main research focuses on the Molecular Genetics and Epidemiology in cancer and autoimmune disease.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/LongJun-Photo.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3332"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Long-Jun Wu </strong>is an Assistant Professor at the Department of Cell Biology &amp; Neuroscience, Rutgers University, USA. His research focuses on the microglia-neuron communication the brain, with particular interests in microglia function in neuropathic pain, brain injury, and memory.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Wei-Hsiung-Yang.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-4139"/><p></p><p><strong>Dr. Wei-Hsiung Yang</strong> is an Assistant Professor, Mercer University School of Medicine, USA. His research interests are establishing the principle of tumor suppressors relay between FOX proteins and non coding RNA, Regulation of post-translational protein modifications, Identifying the cancer-causing genes, tumor-suppressive genes, targets, pathways and novel regulators of p53 tumor suppressor.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Dr.-Tushar-Patil.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17548"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Tushar Patil</strong> is an Assistant Professor of Neurology at Jawaharlal Nehru Medical College, Wardha, India. He did his Neurology residency from King George’s Medical University, Lucknow, India. His research interests include Tropical Neurology, Neuroimmunology, Epilepsy, Stroke and Snake envenomation.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Razmkon_Ali.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-18163"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Ali Razmkon</strong> is an Assistant Professor of Neurosurgery, Department of Neurosurgery, Division of functional Neurosurgery &amp; Neuro-oncology,  Shiraz University of Medical Sciences, Iran. His main research interests include neurosurgery, spine, movement disorders, pain, epilepsy, brain tumors and head trauma.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/edited6.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3415"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Sheng Zhang</strong> is an Associate Research Scientist at the Department of Psychiatry, Yale University School of Medicine, USA. His research focuses on combining psychophysics, neural imaging, computation to understand how brain works at the systems level, ingenious exploratory analyses of neuro imaging data &amp; how these analytical methods may contribute to the pathogenesis of substance.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Photo-Yujing-Li.-jpg.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3459"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Yujing Li</strong> is a Senior Scientist at the Department of human Genetics, School of Medicine Emory University, USA.  His  research interests include molecular genetics, neuroscience, epigenetics, and chemical biology approach towards dissection of RNA i pathway.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/22.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3550"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Rui Chang</strong> is a Member of Cell Biology Department, Harvard Medical school, USA. His research interest includes how external (such as nutrients,irritant chemicals) or internal(such as blood pressure, pH) cues are detected and transmitted to the brain  by vague nerve.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/photo-Qian-Li.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-3590"/></p><p> <strong>Dr. Qian Li</strong> is working at Cell Biology Department, Harvard Medical School, USA. His research interest mainly focuses on cellular trafficking mechanisms of the voltage gated ion channel Nav1.8 that is involved in pain sensation, how the olfactory system controls innate behavior.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Elham-Ataei.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-18170"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Elham Ataei</strong> is a Senior Neurology Assistant at Tehran University of Medical Sciences/ Rasool Akram Hospital, Tehran, Iran. Her research interests in clinical researches and expert in neurologic paraclinical procedures as EMGNCS, EEG and TCCS also she focuses on the academic, precise visiting, treatment of patients.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Aljuboori-1.jpg" alt="" title="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17660"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Zaid Sameer Aljuboori</strong> is a Neurosurgery Resident, Department of Neurosurgery at University of Louisville, USA. His area of research interests in academic neurosurgery which includes Spinal cord injury and Stem cell biology lab. He is motivated and ambitious to utilize knowledge and skills to help patients.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/Gregory-D1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-19545"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Gregory Dendramis</strong> is a cardiologist expert in arrhythmology, cardiac electrophysiology and pacing at the Cardiovascular Division of the University Hospital of Palermo, Italy. He is the author of many international scientific publications and his research has contributed to the expansion of current understandings of ischemic causes of Brugada Phenocopy.</p></div>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1),
(140, 'Instructions to Author', 10, 28, 'instructions-to-author', 'journal-of-syndromes', '<p>Journal of Syndromes (JSYND) provides biannual publication of articles in all areas related to Syndromes. JSYND receives manuscripts that meet the general criteria of significance and scientific excellence. Prior to publication, articles that are in press will be available in open access format at <a href="http://www.avensonline.org/medical/syndromes/articles-in-press-10/">www.avensonline.org/medical/syndromes/articles-in-press-10/</a></p><p>Submit manuscripts online at <a href="http://www.avensonline.org/submit-manuscript">www.avensonline.org/submit-manuscript/</a></p><p>(OR)</p><p></p><p>Submit manuscripts as an e-mail attachment to the Editorial Office at <a href="mailto:editor.jsynd@avensonline.org"> editor.jsynd@avensonline.org</a></p><p></p><p>A manuscript number will be e-mailed to the corresponding author within 72 hours.</p><p></p><p><strong>Avens Publishers Policy Regarding the NIH Mandate</strong></p><p></p><p>Avens Publishers will support authors by posting the published version of articles by NIH grant-holders to PubMed Central immediately after publication.</p><p></p><p><strong>Submission of an Article</strong></p><p></p><p>Submitted articles should have a summary/abstract, separate from the main text, of up to 300 words.<br/>This summary does not include references, numbers, abbreviations or measurements unless essential.<br/>The summary should provide a basic-level introduction to the field; a brief account of the background and principle of the work; a statement of the main conclusions; and 2-3 sentences that place the main findings into a general context. The text may contain a few short subheadings of not more than 40 characters each.</p><p></p><p><strong>Formats for Avens Publishers contributions: Avens Publishers accepts the following:</strong></p><p>– Research Articles</p><p>– Reviews Articles</p><p>– Abstracts</p><p>– Article Commentaries</p><p>– Book Reviews</p><p>– Rapid Communications</p><p>– Letters to the Editor</p><p>– Case Reports</p><p>– Meeting Reports</p><p>– Orations</p><p>– Product Reviews</p><p>– Hypotheses and Analyses.</p><p></p><p><strong>Manuscript Preparation Guidelines</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>Manuscripts should be divided into the following sections:</strong></p><p>All submissions should be accompanied by a 500 words or less cover letter briefly stating the significance of the research, agreement of authors for publication, number of figures and tables, supporting files, and supplementary information.</p><p>Also, include current telephone and fax numbers, as well as postal and E-mail address of corresponding author to maintain communication.</p><p></p><p><strong>Manuscript title</strong></p><p>The title should be limited to 25 words or less and should not contain abbreviations. The title should be a brief phrase describing the contents of the paper.</p><p></p><p><strong>Author Information</strong></p><p>Complete names and affiliation of all authors, including contact details of corresponding author (Telephone, Fax and E-mail address).</p><p></p><p><strong>Abstract</strong></p><p>The Abstract should be informative and completely self-explanatory, briefly present the topic, state the scope of the experiments, indicate significant data, and point out major findings and conclusions. The abstract should summarize the manuscript content in 300 words or less accommodating a description of the study background, methods, results and conclusion. Following the abstract, a list of keywords (3-10) and abbreviations should be included.</p><p></p><p><strong>Introduction</strong></p><p>The introduction should set the tone of the paper by providing a clear statement of the study, the relevant literature on the study subject, and the proposed approach or solution. </p><p></p><p><strong>Materials and Methods</strong></p><p>This section should provide a complete overview of the design of the study. Detailed descriptions of materials or participants, comparisons, interventions and types of analysis should be mentioned. However, only new procedures should be described in detail; previously published procedures should be cited, and important modifications of published procedures should be mentioned briefly. Capitalize trade names and include the manufacturer’s name and address.</p><p></p><p><strong>Results</strong></p><p>The Results section should provide complete details of the experiment that are required to support the conclusion of the study. The results should be written in the past tense when describing findings in the authors’ experiments. Previously published findings should be written in the present tense. Results and Discussion may be combined or in a separate section.</p><p></p><p><strong>Acknowledgements</strong></p><p>This section includes acknowledgment of people, grant details, funds, etc.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong> If an author fails to submit his/her work as per the above instructions, they are pleased to maintain clear titles namely headings, subheading.</p><p></p><p><strong>References</strong></p><p>Only published or accepted manuscripts should be included in the reference list. Meetings abstracts, conference talks, or papers that have been submitted but not yet accepted should not be cited. </p><p></p><p>Avens uses the numbered citation (citation-sequence) method. References are listed and numbered in the order that they appear in the text. In the text, citations should be indicated by the reference number in brackets. Multiple citations within a single set of brackets should be separated by commas. Where there are three or more sequential citations, they should be given as a range. Example: “… now enable biologists to simultaneously monitor the expression of thousands of genes in a single experiment [1,5-7,28].” </p><p></p><p>Authors are requested to provide at least one online link for each reference (preferably PubMed) as all references will be linked electronically as much as possible to the papers they cite. Please use the following style for the reference list:</p><p><strong>Examples:</strong></p><p><strong>Published Papers</strong></p><p></p><p>1. Laemmli UK (1970) Cleavage of structural proteins during the assembly of the head of bacteriophage T4. Nature 227: 680-685.</p><p>2. Brusic V, Rudy G, Honeyman G, Hammer J, Harrison L (1998) Prediction of MHC class II-binding peptides using an evolutionary algorithm and artificial neural network. Bioinformatics 14: 121-130.</p><p>3. Doroshenko V, Airich L, Vitushkina M, Kolokolova A, Livshits V, et al. (2007) YddG from <em>Escherichia coli</em> promotes export of aromatic amino acids. FEMS Microbiol Lett 275: 312-318.</p><p></p><p><strong>Note:</strong> Please list the first five authors and then add “et al.” if there are additional authors.</p><p><strong>Books</strong></p><p>1. Baggot JD (1999) Principles of drug disposition in domestic animals: The basis of Veterinary Clinical Pharmacology. (1stedn), W.B. Saunders company, Philadelphia, London, Toranto.</p><p>2. Zhang Z (2006) Bioinformatics tools for differential analysis of proteomic expression profiling data from clinical samples. Taylor &amp; Francis CRC Press.</p><p><strong>Conference</strong></p><p>Hofmann T (1999) The Cluster-Abstraction Model: unsupervised learning of topic hierarchies from text data. Proceedings of the International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence.</p><p><strong>Tables</strong></p><p>These should be used at a minimum and designed as simple as possible. We strongly encourage authors to submit tables as .doc format. Tables should be self-explanatory without reference to the text. Note: If the submission is in PDF format, the author is requested to retain the same in .doc format in order to aid in completion of process successfully.</p><p><strong>Figures</strong></p><p>The preferred file formats for photographic images are PNG, TIFF and JPEG.</p><p>Use Arabic numerals to designate figures and upper case letters for their parts (Figure 1). Begin each legend with a title and include sufficient description so that the figure is understandable without reading the text of the manuscript. Information given in legends should not be repeated in the text.</p><p><strong>Equations</strong></p><p>Equations should be encoded in MathML format.</p><p><strong>Supplementary Information</strong></p><p>Discrete items of the Supplementary Information (for example, figures, tables) referred to an appropriate point in the main text of the paper.</p><p>Summary diagram/figure included as part of the Supplementary Information (optional).</p><p>All supplementary information should be supplied as a single pdf file, wherever applicable file size within the permitted limits for Supplementary Information. </p><p><strong>Galley Proofs</strong></p><p>Electronic proofs will be sent as an e-mail attachment to the corresponding author as a PDF file. Page proofs are considered to be the final version of the manuscript. With the exception of typographical or minor clerical errors, no changes will be made in the manuscript at the proof stage. </p>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1),
(141, 'Manuscript Work Flow', 10, 28, 'manuscript-work-flow', 'journal-of-syndromes', '<p>Once a manuscript is submitted, it is assigned to one of our Eminent Editorial Board members to check the  Genuinity, novelty and quality of research. The manuscript is evaluated by the respective editor with in two days of submission. If the manuscript meets the standards of Avens, further proceeding of the manuscript is carried out. The status of acceptance/ rejection will be intimated by the editorial office.</p><p> <br/></p><p>    The accepted manuscripts are peer reviewed by the experts assigned by the editor.  The time for peer review processing is 14 days. The comments given by the reviewer decides the fate of article towards the possible publication. If at least two reviewers support and ensure the quality and recommend for the publication, the article is processed and published without any changes with editor’s approval.</p><p> <br/></p><p>    If the reviewer suggest for the revision (minor/major) the corresponding author will be notified to make the desirable changes in the manuscript towards publication.</p><p> <br/></p><p>   The manuscript will be rejected if more than two reviewers express their disapproval towards the publication. However the editor approval is mandatory for the publication at any stage. Avens is committed to its 45 to 60 days publication process.</p>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1),
(142, 'Home', 10, 29, 'home', 'journal-of-urology-nephrology', '<p>Journal of Urology &amp; Nephrology is an international, Online Open Access, peer reviewed journal that provides current information of research, development and treatment aspects that are involved in the fields of urology and nephrology.</p><p><span style="color: #cc5200;"><strong>Editor-in-Chief</strong></span></p><table border="1" width="650" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="1"><tbody><tr><td><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9171" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bli.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Benyi Li</strong> is an Associate Professor with Tenure in the Department of Urology, University of Kansas Medical Center at Kansas City, Kansas. Following practice as an Urologist for more than 10 years in his earlier career, Dr Li’s research in recent 15 years has been focusing on development of novel therapies for prostate cancer-specific targeted treatment.</td></tr></tbody></table><p><span style="color: #cc5200;"><strong>Indexed in: </strong></span></p><ul><li><a href="http://journalseek.net/cgi-bin/journalseek/journalsearch.cgi?query=2380-0585&amp;field=title&amp;editorID=&amp;send=Search+Title%2FISSN+Only" target="_blank">Genamics JournalSeek</a></li><li><a href="http://www.icmje.org/journals-following-the-icmje-recommendations/ " target="_blank">ICMJE</a></li><li><a href="http://www.worldcat.org/title/journal-of-urology-nephrology/oclc/913744413&amp;referer=brief_results " target="_blank">WorldCat</a></li><li><a href="http://www.sherpa.ac.uk/romeo/journals.php?la=en&amp;fIDnum=|&amp;mode=simple&amp;id=2458&amp;letter=ALL" target="_blank">SHERPA/RoMEO</a></li><li><a href="http://jgateplus.com/search/footer-html/PublisherPartners.jsp" target="_blank">J-Gate</a></li><li><a href="http://www.researchbib.com/view/issn/2380-0585" target="_blank">Research Bible</a></li><li><a href="https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?hl=en&amp;q=avensonline.org&amp;btnG= " target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></li><li><a href="http://www.academickeys.com/" target="_blank">AcademicKeys</a></li><li><a href="http://jandc.pubshub.com/Home" target="_blank">PubsHub</a></li><li><a href="http://www.drji.org/BrowseAllJournals.aspx" target="_blank">Directory of Research Journals Indexing</a></li><li><a href="http://miar.ub.edu/" target="_blank">MIAR</a></li></ul>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1),
(143, 'Aims & Scope', 10, 29, 'aims-scope', 'journal-of-urology-nephrology', '<p>Journal of Urology &amp; Nephrology provides current information of research, development and treatment aspects that are involved in the fields of urology and nephrology.</p><p>Topics covered in this Journal include, but are not limited to:</p><ul><li>Kidney Diseases</li><li>Prostatic Diseases</li><li>Transplantation</li><li>Urinary Tract Stones</li><li>Reconstructive Surgery</li><li>Chronic Kidney Disease</li><li>Tubulointerstitial Disorders</li><li>Case Reports</li><li>Calculus</li><li>Collapsing glomerulosclerosis</li><li>Cystic renal dysplasia</li><li>Diabetic glomerulosclerosis</li><li>Hydronephrosis</li><li>Interstitial nephritis</li><li>Nephrostomy</li><li>Peritoneal dialysis</li><li>Prostatitis</li><li>Steal syndrome</li><li>Oiding cystourethrogram</li><li>Dialysis</li><li>Fistula</li><li>Kidney failure</li><li>Nephrotoxins</li><li>Onconephrology</li><li>Renal transplantation</li></ul>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1),
(144, 'Editorial Board', 10, 29, 'editorial-board', 'journal-of-urology-nephrology', '<div class="eb-box"><p><span style="color: #cc5200;"><strong>Editor-in-Chief</strong></span></p><table border="1" width="650" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="1"><tbody><tr><td><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9171" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bli.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Benyi Li</strong> is an Associate Professor with Tenure in the Department of Urology, University of Kansas Medical Center at Kansas. He practiced as Urologist for more than 10 years in his earlier career. His research in recent 15 years has been focusing on development of novel therapies for prostate cancer-specific targeted treatment.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-7022" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Osama1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Osama AL-Omar</strong> is Director of Pediatric Urology and Assistant Professor of Surgery at West Virginia University School of Medicine. He has a special interest in pediatric urology including external genitalia reconstructive surgery, fetal evaluation of urological anomalies, vesicoureteral reflux, UTI, ureteropelvic junction obstructions, spina bifida and neurogenic bladder, and kidney and bladder stones.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-16865" title="Tie1" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Tie1-300x290.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="290"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Reza Roshandel </strong> is an Chief Urology resident at Imam Reza Medical Center, Tabriz University of medical sciences, Tabriz, Iran. He is also junior resident in urology of European Association of Urology &amp; Member of The Medical Council of the Islamic Republic of Iran. He has a special interest in endourology including urinary stones, prostate diseases and prostate cancer, and reconstructive surgery.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6603" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Gupta-photograph-2.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Sanjay Gupta</strong> is Carter Kissell Professor &amp; Research Director in the Department of Urology at the Case Western Reserve University. He also holds secondary appointments in the Departments of Nutrition &amp; Division of General Medical Sciences at Case Comprehensive Cancer Center. His research is primarily on prostate &amp; bladder cancer.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2091" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Awaiting5.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Kwang Myeong Kim</strong> is a Professor in the Department of Urology at the Seoul National University &amp; University Children’s Hospital. He has expertise in pediatric urologic disease and has a special interest in voiding dysfunction in children. His research is primarily on renal and bladder function in obstructed bladder.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9133" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Moore_Robert1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Robert Moore</strong> is a Director of Clinical Urology &amp; Urology Residency Site Director at the Salisbury VA as well as Associate Professor at Wake Forest University. He is one of the early innovators of minimally invasive surgical approaches to renal disease. His outcomes research on minimally invasive renal procedures demonstrated improved patient recovery &amp; equal clinical outcomes to their open counterpart.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9809" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Grasso.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Marco Grasso</strong> is the Chief of the Department of Urology, San Gerardo Hospital, Monza, Italy. He has always been involved in research particularly in the field of oncology, andrology as well as in the pathophysiology of the urogenital tract studying contractile activity of isolated organs in vitro. He is a Member of the European Board of Urology.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-10012" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/photo.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Herney Andres Garcia-Perdomo</strong> is a Professor of Urology and Clinical Epidemiology at University of Valle, Colombia. He is the director of the Cochrane associate group at University of Valle. He has special interest in reconstructive surgery, cancer and female urology and also in clinical research: clinical trials and evidence synthesis methods (systematic reviews and Meta-analysis).</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-7224" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/ltak3qrm.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Naheed Ansari</strong> is an Associate Professor of Clinical Medicine in Albert Einstein College of Medicine. Her project is mainly on multi-center trial involving role of Biomarkers (IL-18 and NGAL) in Patients with End Stage Liver Disease with Acute Kidney Injury. She is a member of American Society of Nephrology &amp; NEPHROLPLUS.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-12004" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Untitled10.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Sung Tae Cho</strong> is an Associate Professor of Urology at the Hallym University, Gangwon, Republic of Korea. He has recently completed animal research on micrRNA-93 under the supervision of Dr. William D. Steers at the University of Virginia (2013-14). His research interests include neurourology, female urology and sex medicine.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-16061" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chughtai.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Bilal Chughtai</strong> is an Assistant Professor of Urology in the Department of Urology at Weill Cornell Medical College, New York Presbyterian Hospital. He has specializes in Voiding Dysfunction, Female Urology, and Neurourology. His research interests include urololgy, urogynecology, general urology, Pelvic Organ Prolapse, Urinary Incontinence, Sexual Dysfunction, Reconstructive Surgery, Infections &amp; Inflammation.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6630" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Sanjeev-Shukla1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Sanjeev Shukla</strong> is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Urology at the Case Western Reserve University &amp; University Hospitals Case Medical Center. His research interest broadly involves urological complications including prostate cancer. Basic research side focus is to develop appropriate biomarkers for early detection and prognosis of prostate cancer.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6735" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/RCL1014-VITALY-MARGULIS1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Vitaly Margulis</strong> is an Assistant Professor of Department of Urology at UT Southwestern Medical Center. His research projects include clinical and lab research focused on the biology of kidney cancer, the genetic changes that occur and cause it to spread, and how to stop it. He uses minimally invasive techniques to treat patients with soft-tissue tumors.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6766" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lee.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Seung Hwan Lee</strong> is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Urology, Yonsei University College of Medicine Gangnam Severance Hospital. He is specialized in urologic oncology, BPH (Benign prostatic hyperplasia), &amp; sexual dysfunction. Currently he is the member of Korean Urological association, Korean prostatic society &amp; Korean association of endourology.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-8172" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Chi-for-JUN-2013.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Yuling Chi</strong> is working as Assistant Professor in the Department of Medicine, Division of Nephrology, Albert Einstein College of Medicine of Yeshiva University. Her current research focuses on the investigation of the role of prostaglandin transporter (PGT) in vascular biology and wound healing under physiological and pathological conditions including cardiovascular disorders and diabetes.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6901" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/mollapom11.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Mehdi Mollapour</strong> is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Urology at the SUNY Upstate Medical University, USA. He is interested in understanding the role of the molecular chaperone Hsp90 in prostate cancer and hereditary types of kidney cancer. He is a member of different professional societies like American Association for Cancer Research and Society for Basic Urologic Research.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-7037" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/El-Zawahry.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Ahmed El-Zawahry</strong> is an Assistant Professor of Surgery at Southern Illinois University specializes in urinary incontinence in men &amp; women, voiding dysfunction, female urology, urodynamics &amp; neurourology. He is a member of several medical societies, including the American Urology Association, Society of Urodynamics, Female Pelvic Medicine, Urogenital Reconstruction &amp; American Urogynecologic Society.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-16070" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Harley-Photo-258x300.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="300"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Kevin Harley</strong> is a Assistant Clinical Professor,nephrologist and internist at the University of California Irvine Medical Center. He has a special interest in acute and chronic renal disease, glomerulonephritis, hemo- and peritoneal dialysis, post-transplant disease, and pregnancy in CKD. His interests include patient and fellow education, transitions in care, and acute and chronic kidney disease management.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-7038" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/WVU1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Mohamad Waseem Salkini</strong> is an Assistant Professor of surgery/urology and the Director of minimally invasive and robotic surgery at West Virginia University College of Medicine. His clinical interest mainly includes Bladder Cancer, Urologic Cancers, Urologic Oncology and Urology. He graduated in 1998 from Damascus University Medical School and finished urology residency training in May 2003.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2091" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Awaiting5.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Sylvia O. Suadicani</strong> is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Urology and Dominick P. Purpura Department of Neuroscience at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine. Her research interest is in the pathophysiology of intercellular signaling and her current research focuses on urothelial biology and pathophysiology.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-23722" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/Untitled3.png" alt="Untitled" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Jae Hyung Chang</strong> is a transplant nephrologist and an Assistant Professor of Medicine at Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons, New York, USA. His research interests include cellular and molecular pathomechanisms involved in development of chronic kidney disease associated with diabetes.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-7752" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/lee-wk1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Won Ki Lee</strong> is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Urology at the Hallym University and Hallym University Chuncheon Sacred Heart Hospital, Korea. The main focus of his clinical and research interests lies in the urologic oncology, especially renal cell carcinoma, and sexual dysfunction, especially erectile dysfunction and premature ejaculation.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6763" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/photo1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Lampros P. Mitrakas</strong> is a Scientific Associate of Urology Department, University of Thessaly, University Hospital of Larissa, Greece and he works as Facharzt in the Academic Hospital of Bamberg, Germany. He is expertised in Endourology in Germany. He has special interest in urogenital malignancies. His research on urinary bladder cancer is awarded with a scholarship by the Hellenic Urological Association (HUA).</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6902" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Peters11.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Inga Peters</strong> currently is a resident in training at the Department of Urology and Urologic Oncology of the Hannover Medical School, Germany. Her research interests are the investigation of putative epigenetic biomarkers in renal cell carcinoma and the development and improvement of imaging diagnostic tools for the detection of prostate cancer.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9161" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Untitled8.png" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Haresh Thummar</strong> is a genitourinary surgeon, Advanced Endourology Fellowship at Mount Sinai hospitals and Ichan school of medicine,by World Society of Endourology. He has much experience in urology of more than 14 years with more than 5000 surgeries and presented more than 50 papers. His Special interest in endourology,urolithiasis,innovation and research, Laparoscopic transplantation, Urooncology, Andrology.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9161" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/stamatiouk1.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Konstantinos Stamatiou</strong> is a specialist urologist. He currently works as a Medical Officer at Tzaneio Hospital, Piraeus, Greece. He has special interest in malignant and benign prostatic diseases. His doctoral research on prostate cancer was awarded by the Hellenic Urological Association (HUA). He is currently conducting research on prostatic inflammation.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-9961" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Akbarov.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/><strong>Dr. Ilgar Akbarov</strong> is an specialist Urologist, Head of Unit 1 (Private Unit) in the Department of Urology, University Hospital of Cologne, Germany and have additional designation for drug treatment in the Uro-Oncology (Chemotherapy), expertise for radiation protection and expertise for emergency services.</p></div><div class="eb-box"><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-17287" title="" src="http://www.avensonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/YasinAydogmus.jpg" alt="" width="100" height="100"/></p><p><strong>Dr. Yasin Aydogmus</strong>, is a specialist/urologist. He currentlyworks at Etimesgut Military Hospital, Ankara, Turkey. He has special interest in pediatric urology, endourology/stonedisease, neurourology and andrology. He is currently conducting research on overactive bladder, nocturnalenuresis.</p></div>', '2016-10-22', '2016-10-22', 1);
